Description: Cypriot terracotta figure of goddess with uplifted arms and headdress. Handmade in primitive style. Missing both arms, nose and body below chest. Very eroded. Pale pink-buff fabric with abundant dark grey, white and red inclusions.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Temple of Aphrodite (Naukratis), Context Φ16 or 17
Curator's comments: Many close parallels exist of this flat-chested type at Yeroskipou-Monagri, south-west Cyprus (Karageorghis 1998, 15-17, pls 8.7-11 Types I(i)77-80), the goddess with uplifted arms type continued from the ‘11th down to the early 5th centuries BC, with very few changes’ (ibid. 17). This example is most likely from the Cypro-Archaic II period. See also British Museum AES 50122 Karageorghis, V. 1998. The coroplastic art of ancient Cyprus. VI. The Cypro-Archaic period small female figurines. Nicosia, University of Cyprus.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (DA.001) (Phase 1)
Condition: fair (incomplete -head and shoulders missing; arms broken)
